        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-22 16:49:48.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nHmm - well I guess the dashes can be there. Looks like SDC doesn't use dashes in their CSAR.",
        "patchset_number": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "5e08a3c15e48b442be1ce1914c4238454bd57fa5",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 1441,
          "name": "Chenfei Gao",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "cgao@research.att.com",
          "username": "cgao"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-22 16:58:19.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nAccording to tosca spec Sec. 3.8.1 and 3.9.1, I think we should add the dash since they are all taken as list. For policies, we already have them as list, but i don't know why policy_types and data_types have them as object, not list. The deserialization would be different with and without dash. With dash, it could be parsed as JsonArray. Without dash, it would be JsonObject. Maybe SDC missed that?",
        "patchset_number": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "74ebc56f5718523098cce973076826ba6c7209cd",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 1441,
          "name": "Chenfei Gao",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "cgao@research.att.com",
          "username": "cgao"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-22 17:00:39.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\nCurrently, I am doing deseriliazation assuming they are all lists. If SDC insists policy_types and data_types not be the list. I can adapt the code accordingly. But that would not strictly follow tosca spec then.",
        "patchset_number": 6
      },
      {
